    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>It's interesting to me that the exact same photo appeared on the front page of the New York Times a few months ago, but no one complained. I'm personally mixed on whether the photos of such individuals should even be released at all in the first place, but this one has already been so--so that argument holds no weight. And, in this case, it shows that he wasn't some deformed monster living in an underground lair but a formerly normal person who had become radicalized. And that makes you think more and reduces the default tendency to "other." Moreover, magazines have featured individuals responsible for the deaths of far more people--and in more unambiguously positive lights. Take, for example, George W. Bush.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:646204">Liberty Equality Fraternity and Trees</a> on <a href="/comments/1224492/50775689#c28">Wed Jul 17, 2013 at 02:14:03 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	





<li id="c29">
