  <a href="/user/uid:9240">Yoshimi</a>, <a href="/user/uid:339452">Mike Kahlow</a>, <a href="/user/uid:141635">greengemini</a>, <a href="/user/uid:549941">Batya the Toon</a>, <a href="/user/uid:14683">smartalek</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>There are a few problems I have.</p>
<p>1. I've seen pictures of him before. He's not physically ugly. But I've also seen the way the magazine industry messes around with pictures of people. What upsets me, as simple as it might seem, is the lighting. They deliberately set the soft lighting of that picture to make it look like it was taken of a rock star in the 1970s.</p>
<p>2. This is not just on the Rolling Stones, per se, but I feel I must point out that the difference in the way we portray white male killers and men of color on the covers of magazines in this country is messed up. As Mona Eltahawy pointed out on Twitter, the way Time Magazine portrayed innocent Egyptians protesting as vicious animals was way more offensive than this picture. When was the last time a killer who was nonwhite was made to look like this on the covers of magazines?</p>
<p>I guess, in the end, my problem is that we only seem to want to humanize white killers.</p>

  </div>
