    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>'Vogue'.</p>
<p>By virtue of being on the cover, you are granted all the expertise of the best photo/image editors, get a stylistic appeal that goes above and beyond the original image, and by virtue of that gain instant celebrity status.</p>
<p>I agree with those who say that the image DOES glorify him it depicts him as a rock star--the terms 'terrorist' 'monster' 'bomber' notwithstanding. &nbsp;The picture is what you see--not the words. &nbsp;And the magazine editors know this.</p>
<p>The original pictures of him are hardly that glamorous.</p>
<p>The examples people cite here, Hitler, Bin Laden, Mc Veigh, etc. etc....all of these images show normal looking people. &nbsp;As they might appear in the news (not in mugshots, not in high-style publications)</p>
<p>This example elevates the portrayal to rock-star status by design. &nbsp;Anyone pretending not to see that is choosing not to see it.</p>
<p>That said, of course the RS can put whatever it wants on its cover. &nbsp;But I'm not surprised a bunch of people are pissed about it--(and hardly just right wingers).</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
